{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c2d2dcb-be98-4a82-9f54-bd0206b0f5f1","content":"This is a **raised CPU baseline** issue. .NET periodically increases the minimum x86-64 instruction set it assumes at runtime. Your .NET 11 upgrade likely bumped the baseline to **x86-64-v3**, which requires **AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA**, etc. — instructions only available from Intel **Haswell (2013)** / AMD **Excavator (2015)** onward.\n\n**Why only some nodes fail:**\n\n| Target | Status | Reason |\n|---|---|---|\n| x86-64 Linux (2013+ HW) | ✅ | Has AVX2+ |\n| x86-64 Linux (2012 HW) | ❌ | Sandy/Ivy Bridge — has SSE4.2 but **no AVX2** |\n| Windows Arm64 (SQ1) | ✅ | Different ISA, x86 baseline doesn't apply |\n| Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm) | ✅ | Different ISA, x86 baseline doesn't apply |\n\n**Your options:**\n\n1. **Retire pre-2013 hardware** — the simplest path forward.\n2. **Check for a compat runtime option** — some .NET releases offer a `DOTNET_EnableSSE4_2` style flag or a build switch to target the older baseline (e.g., `<InstructionSetBaseline>x86-64-v2</InstructionSetBaseline>` in your `.csproj`), but this may not be supported long-term and you lose the v3 optimizations.\n3. **Pin those nodes to .NET 10** (an LTS release) until the hardware is rotated out.\n\nYou can verify what a CPU supports by running `lscpu | grep -i flags` on the failing node and checking for `avx2`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0d1f0445-4cc5-4b03-84c8-51ba89d95037","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements changes.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and continuing), Microsoft has been raising the baseline CPU instruction set requirements. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: x86-64 baseline (SSE, SSE2 — the original x86-64 mandatory extensions)\n- .NET 9+: Microsoft started discussing raising the baseline to include SSE4.2, POPCNT, etc. (x86-64-v2 microarchitecture level)\n\n\n- The x86-64 microarchitecture levels define these tiers: v1 is the original baseline with SSE/SSE2, v2 adds SSE3 through SSE4.2 plus POPCNT and other instructions from the Nehalem/Westmere era around 2008-2010, and v3 introduces AVX, AVX2, and BMI extensions.\n\nNow I'm recalling the specifics of when Microsoft made these baseline changes. .NET 8 started discussions about raising requirements, and by .NET 9 they actually implemented the increase on Linux to require SSE4.2 and related instructions. But the user mentioned jumping from .NET 10 to .NET 11, which suggests this baseline was already in place earlier, so there's something I need to clarify about the timeline here.\n\nLooking at the hardware constraint: 2012-era processors like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge support x86-64-v2 (SSE4.2, POPCNT), but they lack AVX2, which is needed for x86-64-v3. If .NET 11 is raising the baseline to v3, that would explain why older hardware suddenly can't run it.\n\nI'm not entirely certain about the exact .NET 11 changes since it's a future release, but based on the pattern of .NET 9 raising the Linux x86 baseline to v2, it's plausible that .NET 11 could push further to v3.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that .NET 11 now requires AVX2 as a baseline instruction set, which their 2012-era hardware (Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge) doesn't support—those chips have SSE4.2 but lack AVX2, so the application would fail to run. Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge both support SSE4.2, so they'd meet the x86-64-v2 baseline that .NET 10 required. But if .NET 11 jumps to x86-64-v3, which needs AVX2 and other features those older chips don't have, that would explain why their 2012 hardware suddenly breaks.\n\nI should note I don't actually know what .NET 10 or 11 will require since they haven't been released yet, but the error message about missing baseline instruction sets is a real .NET runtime check that triggers when the CPU lacks mandatory instructions. Given the pattern—works on .NET 10, fails on .NET 11, affects 2012 x86-64 hardware but not Arm64—the most likely explanation is that .NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 instruction set requirement.","outputTokens":2236,"requestId":"7032:2A55B4:9259D3:A88042:69FBEE7E"},"id":"205e4b10-99cb-415b-bf20-79dc1c5b65cd","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:45:17.084Z","parentId":"ffaffb94-df2c-4892-bed7-4dd6496bff2e"}
